\begin_layout Subsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once upon a time, in the mythical land of Europe, there was the kingdom
 of Trainsylvania.
 It was of harsh mountains, black forests, horror tropes, inconsistent tone,
 and poor writing.
 It was also lawless, and of chaos.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once upon a time, there was a vampire whose name was ‘Dracula’.
 He awoke after his millenia sleep, in his castle – which, due to ancient
 magicks, had never been discovered.
 He awoke to a land without order; a land which had forgotten vampires had
 ever existed at all.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dracula bade his time and encouraged the seeds of evil to flourish in ancient
 Trainsylvania.
 The wolves, the necromancers, the ghouls: all returned.
 And finally, he awoke his feared children, with a challenge, a promise,
 and a threat: whichever of them could drain this cursed land of the most
 blood, by time they could no longer hide themselves and would operate in
 the open, would serve alongside Dracula for a thousand years.
 The remainder would be served with potatoes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Real world overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
18Dracula is an 18XX game that, instead of being about trains, is about
 playing blood sucking vampires.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It’s loosely based on 1830.
 Its most major departure from other 18XX games is that it uses a fixed
 map with defined routes instead of tiles.
 The primary reason for this is as an experiment to make an 18XX game that
 is more accessible for people with low or no vision – and the jury is out
 on whether it is effective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also a little more intention to be perhaps a little less balanced
 and offer a few odder choices than most 18XX games.
 There is a bit more variety in monsters than 1830 trains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of train companies, you will have stock in fronts.
 Instead of privates, you have associates.
 Instead of trains, you have monsters.
 Instead of dollars, you have pints (of blood, that is).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we can get on the same page – it’s a little bit silly.
 And that’s quite intentional.
 There are plenty of serious 18XX games that you can have hundreds of plays
 of, but this is a slightly silly one to play once or twice a year on Halloween.
 Hopefully you can have a little fun with it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Medieval Edition is trying to give 18Dracula some more fangs.
 The first edition got very slow around the middle, and it was unusual to
 be in a position where you may go bankrupt.
 The goals of this edition are to make the rules more clear and quick to
 follow, add some more feeling of choice in your selection of routes, but
 most importantly - to make the game go faster, in part by making it stay
 more cutthroat throughout.
\end_layout

